## Germplasm Phenotype:
   - [elc]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;About 2% of all trichomes had more than one nucleus. Among the cluster-like trichomes, 93% had several nuclei, whereas 0.4% of the trichomes with a normal appearance had more than one nucleus.
   - [elc]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;In the mutant, about 2% of the trichomes showed a cluster phenotype. In clusters, two stems were usually formed that appeared to separate just above the epidermal surface giving the trichome a moose-horn-like appearance.
   - [elc]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;The mutant has slightly less branching of trichomes than in wild type.
   - [elc kis-T1]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;Epidermal pavement cells are strongly reduced in size.
   - [elc kis-T1]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;Increase in the frequency of trichomes with more stems.
   - [elc kis-T1]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;Leaf architecture is grossly disturbed.
   - [elc kis-T1]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;Many cells contain multiple nuclei and nuclear anomalies.
   - [elc kis-T1]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;Synergistic phenotype compared to both single mutants.
   - [elc sti]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;The mutant showed cluster-like trichomes lacking additional branches. 
   - [kak elc]()&nbsp;---&nbsp;The double mutant exhibits an additive trichome phenotype. The cluster frequency and number of nuclei was similar to that in elc single mutants and the number of branches was similar to that in kak single mutants.
